<div class="dl-page">

  <!-- HEADER -->
  <header class="dl-header">
    <h1>The Bitcoin <em>Doubling</em> Ladder</h1>
    <p class="dl-subtitle">You've met <a href="/the-power-law.html">the Power Law</a>. This page looks at it through a single lens &mdash; price doublings &mdash; with three visuals that make its behavior tangible: where each doubling has landed, how far the market strays from the trend, and what the pattern is (and isn't) telling you.</p>
  </header>

  <!-- ATTRIBUTION (prominent, near the top) -->
  <div class="dl-attribution">
    <div class="dl-attribution-label">Lineage &amp; attribution</div>
    <p>This page builds directly on the doubling-cadence framing of <strong>Matthew Mezinskis</strong> (<a href="https://www.porkopolis.io/thechart/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Porkopolis Economics &middot; porkopolis.io/thechart</a>), whose published table first laid the per-doubling progression out as a ladder. The underlying power-law theory it rests on originates with <strong>Dr.&nbsp;Giovanni Santostasi</strong>, and the earliest logarithmic-regression sketch of Bitcoin's price came from the pseudonymous <strong>Trolololo</strong> (<a href="https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=831547.0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BitcoinTalk, 2014</a>). The reframing, the deviation analysis, and any errors here are this site's own.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- THESIS -->
  <section class="dl-hero">
    <div class="dl-hero-stat">Each price doubling takes a fixed <em>percentage</em> longer in days &mdash; not a fixed number of years.</div>
    <p class="dl-hero-body">Mezinskis spotted it first: laid out as a ladder, bitcoin's price doublings come at a steady cadence &mdash; each one takes about <strong>12.8% more</strong> of bitcoin's life than the last. Not magic &mdash; arithmetic, as we'll show. What this page adds is a way to <em>see</em> it: where each doubling has actually landed, and how far the market strays from the line along the way.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT IT IS (and isn't) -->
  <section class="dl-section">
    <h2>A fingerprint, not a clock</h2>
    <p>Each 12.8% of additional age has doubled the price. That's the whole pattern &mdash; and it's a fact about the math, not a habit of the market.</p>
    <aside class="dl-mathbox">
      <div class="dl-mathbox-title">The one line of math, if you want it</div>
      <p>The trend is <em>price = a &middot; day<sup>b</sup></em> (<em>day</em> = age since the Genesis block, 3&nbsp;Jan&nbsp;2009; <em>b</em>&nbsp;&asymp;&nbsp;5.76). Doubling the price means <em>day</em> must grow by <em>2<sup>1/b</sup> = 2<sup>1/5.76</sup> &asymp; 1.128</em> &mdash; about 12.8% &mdash; every time.</p>
    </aside>
    <div class="dl-insight">
      <p>The ~12.8%-per-doubling cadence isn't bitcoin keeping time. It is what <em>any</em> power law of exponent 5.76 must do, by algebra alone.</p>
    </div>
    <p>A fixed 12.8% of a growing age means each doubling takes <em>longer in calendar time</em> than the last: 128 days when the network was 1,000 days old, but 766 days when it was 6,000 days old. The cadence is constant in <em>proportion</em> and stretching in years. The ladder is the Power Law trend line, marked with a step at each price doubling &mdash; a record of past doublings, with the steps extrapolated forward. Not a schedule; a consequence of the curve.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- VISUAL A — THE DOUBLING LADDER -->
  <div class="dl-chart-container">
    <div class="dl-chart-kicker">Visual A</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-title">The Doubling Ladder</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-subtitle">The trend's price doublings as a log-log staircase, from $0.06 to a projected ~$2M. Diamonds mark where the market <em>actually</em> first reached each rung &mdash; left of a rung means it got there early, in a mania; right means it lagged. Hover any rung for the lead or lag in days.</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-wrapper" data-chart-copy data-chart-title="The Bitcoin doubling ladder"><canvas id="ladderChart"></canvas></div>
    <div class="dl-chart-source"><strong>Read it like a stylus on a record:</strong> the amber staircase is where the trend says each level &ldquo;should&rdquo; arrive. The green diamonds &mdash; clustered far to the left in 2011 and 2013 and 2017 &mdash; are the manias overshooting years ahead of schedule. The 2017 run reached $15,729 roughly <strong>1,089 days</strong> before the trend did. The blue line is bitcoin's monthly high &mdash; watch it rocket through several rungs at once in each mania, then sag below the staircase in the bears. Source: trend levels from <em>price = 1.69&times;10<sup>&minus;17</sup> &middot; day<sup>5.763</sup></em>; first-crossing dates and monthly highs from daily history (Blockchain.info, all-time).</div>
  </div>

  <!-- THE TURN — gravity not clockwork -->
  <section class="dl-section">
    <h2>Gravity, not clockwork</h2>
    <p>If the ladder is &ldquo;just algebra,&rdquo; where is the genuinely remarkable part? Here: across more than fifteen years, the <em>actual</em> price has spent the whole time misbehaving &mdash; overshooting wildly in every mania, crashing far below in every bear market &mdash; and yet, averaged over its entire life, it sits almost exactly <strong>on</strong> the trendline.</p>
    <p class="dl-pull">The trend doesn't tick like a clock. It pulls like <em>gravity</em>. Price is always somewhere it shouldn't be, and always being dragged back &mdash; reversion to the mean.</p>
    <p>Measure the distance from trend month by month &mdash; <em>ln(actual&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;trend)</em> &mdash; and the record is anything but orderly. It is a series of enormous excursions: up to <strong>+2.5</strong> in the 2011 and 2013 frenzies (roughly twelve times the trend), down past <strong>&minus;0.9</strong> in the deepest bear troughs <em>(the wave plots ln(actual&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;trend), so +2.5 means about 12&times; above the line; &minus;0.9 means roughly 0.4&times;)</em>. But sum all 191 months and the mean log-deviation is <strong>+0.014</strong> &mdash; just a whisker above the line. The median month sits <em>slightly below</em> trend; only about <strong>41%</strong> of months close above it. The average is held near zero not by calm, but by a few violent overshoots balancing many quiet undershoots.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- VISUAL B — THE DEVIATION WAVE (centerpiece) -->
  <div class="dl-chart-container">
    <div class="dl-chart-kicker">Visual B &middot; centerpiece</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-title">The Deviation Wave</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-subtitle">Not price in a band &mdash; the <em>gap</em> itself. Each month's distance above or below the trendline, as a wave straddling a zero centerline. Green is the market above trend; red is below. The dashed line is the 15-year average. The vertical axis is <em>ln(actual&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;trend)</em> &mdash; above 0 means the market sits above the trend &mdash; and the ticks read as a multiple of trend (&times;2, &times;4), with the log value in parentheses.</div>
    <div class="dl-chart-wrapper" data-chart-copy data-chart-title="The deviation wave"><canvas id="waveChart"></canvas></div>
    <div class="dl-wave-stats">
      <span class="dl-wave-stat"><span class="dl-wave-swatch above"></span> Above trend: <strong>41.9%</strong> of months (80)</span>
      <span class="dl-wave-stat"><span class="dl-wave-swatch below"></span> Below trend: <strong>58.1%</strong> of months (111)</span>
      <span class="dl-wave-stat">Mean: <strong>+0.014</strong> ln &middot; essentially zero</span>
    </div>
    <div class="dl-chart-source"><strong>This is the centerpiece, and it is deliberately not the channel chart.</strong> The Power Law's channel shows price riding inside a corridor. This shows the corridor subtracted away &mdash; only the deviation remains. The shape is the argument: tall green spikes that don't last, broad red shallows that do, and a long-run average pinned to the line. Month-end closes vs. the trendline; 191 months, mid-2010 to mid-2026.</div>
    <div class="dl-trendnote">
      <p><strong>The ceiling is falling; the floor holds.</strong> Each mania has overshot the trend less than the last &mdash; about 9&times; in 2011, 4&times; in 2017, 3&times; in 2021 &mdash; while every bear has bottomed near 0.4&times; of trend. The wave is compressing from the top: bitcoin's overshoots are shrinking as the asset matures, even as its floor stays remarkably constant. The dashed green line fits the four cycle <em>peaks</em>; the dashed red line fits the four cycle <em>troughs</em>.</p>
      <p class="dl-trendnote-caveat">Four cycles is a small sample, and 2013 overshot more than 2011; read this as a tendency across recent cycles, not a guarantee the ceiling keeps falling.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- WHAT THE GAP IS GOOD FOR — closing insight -->
  <section class="dl-section">
    <h2>What the gap is good for</h2>
    <p>The wave isn't just describing the past &mdash; it's been a rough map of where the risk sat. Two things stand out across fifteen years.</p>
    <p><strong>The swings are shrinking.</strong> The spread of price around the trend has compressed every few years &mdash; from enormous in the early cycles to a fraction of that lately. As bitcoin has grown, its overshoots and undershoots have both pulled in toward the line. (This is the maturing-asset story <a href="/the-bitcoin-horizon.html">The Bitcoin Horizon</a> makes in full: as a network gets adopted, its price stops behaving like a lottery ticket and starts behaving like an asset.)</p>
    <p><strong>Where you stood relative to the trend has mattered.</strong> Historically, the further below the line bitcoin sat, the stronger the years that followed; the further above, the weaker. In the record so far, periods that began well below trend went on to far outpace periods that began well above it. The line behaves like a center of gravity &mdash; stretched far from it, the pull back has tended to be strongest.</p>
    <p>None of this is a signal to act on, and past patterns can break. But it reframes the deviation wave from a curiosity into something with a use: a sense of when the asymmetry has favored patience, and when it has favored caution. That's the discipline <a href="/disciplined-rebalancing.html">Disciplined Rebalancing</a> turns into an explicit, rules-based method &mdash; sell into the highs, buy into the lows, by the channel rather than by feel.</p>
  </section>

